DataEntry objects have 5 different types of load methods, each with different behavior for the specified identifier(s)

DataEntry::load($identifier)                 Will load the DataEntry with the specified identifier from the database.
                                             An identifier is required and the entry MUST exist

DataEntry::loadOrNull($identifier)           Will load the DataEntry with the specified identifier from the database.
                                             An identifier is optional and if specified, the entry MUST exist. NULL
                                             will be returned if the specified identifier is empty

DataEntry::loadOrThis($identifier)           Will load the DataEntry with the specified identifier from the database.
                                             An identifier is optional and if specified, the entry MUST exist. The
                                             empty object will be returned if the specified identifier is empty

DataEntry::loadOrNullInitialize($identifier) Will load the DataEntry with the specified identifier from the database.
                                             An identifier is optional and if specified, and the entry does not
                                             exist, $this empty object will be returned. If the specified identifier
                                             is empty, $this empty object will be returned

DataEntry::loadOrThisInitialize($identifier) Will load the DataEntry with the specified identifier from the database.
                                             An identifier is optional and if specified, and the entry does not
                                             exist, $this empty object will be returned. If the specified identifier
                                             is empty, NULL will be returned

See the identifier / return table below for a comprehensive view of how each method responds.



* Load methods always require an identifier. This identifier can be NULL, integer, string, array, a
  DataIteratorInterface object, or a DataEntryInterface object

* Empty or NULL means no identifier, but also an array identifier for which all values are considered empty. Empty is
  the PHP definition of empty, anything that can be interpreted as null like NULL, FALSE, "", 0, [], etc.

* Empty identifiers are handled differently by each different load method. See the description above, and the table
  below for more information

* If the specified identifier is numeric, it will *always* be used like a database id and checked against the
  database ID column specified in DataEntry::getIdColumn() If the database id is positive, the DataEntry object will
  fetch the data from the database defined in the connector for the object. If the entry is negative and the DataEntry
  object has DataEntry::getConfigurationPath() return a string path, the data will be pulled from the (Yaml)
  configuration files using the string path. If DataEntry::getConfigurationPath() returns NULL, a
  DataEntryInvalidIdentifierException will be thrown instead.

* If the specified identifier is a non numeric string, and the DataEntry::getUniqueColumn() method returns a string
  value, the key will be searched against the DataEntry::getUniqueColumn() instead of the DataEntry::getIdColumn()
  column. If DataEntry::getUniqueColumn() returns NULL, an OutOfBoundsException exception will be thrown. If the method
  DataEntry::getUniqueColumn() returns a column that is not defined in the DataEntry Definitions object, an
  OutOfBoundsException will be thrown.

* If the specified identifier is an array, it should be a [key => value] array with one or more entries. Each entry
  will use the key as an SQL column and the value as the value that the SQL column should have. Care must be taken with
  ensuring that the specified combination (however many keys may be specified) returns 1 or less results. If the
  specified key => value combinations yield multiple results, an SqlMultipleResultsException will be thrown.

* DataIteratorInterface objects will be treated as if they were arrays, internally, the method will
  $identifier = $identifier->getSource() before continuing

* DataEntryInterface objects will be checked first if they are compatible. Compatible means that the class of the
  object is either the current class, or a parent class of the current object. When the specified identifier is a
  parent DataEntryInterface class, it will return the current class with the data from the parent class.
  For example: The class "Accounts\SystemUser" is a child class of the class "Accounts\User". When executing the code
  $user = SystemUser::new()->load(User::new()->load(9238423)); the variable $user will have a system user with the data
  from the user with database id 9238423



